## 5. Coverage Requirements

The specification must be complete enough for an experienced developer to understand and maintain the framework. It must cover:

- Framework purpose, scope, philosophy, objectives, design principles, and major components.
- Overall architecture, processing architecture, module organization, subsystem relationships, execution model, and framework layers.
- Configuration model, runtime cache, global constants, dashboard-derived configuration, feature flags, version constants, and property keys.
- Workflow architecture, process sequence, execution order, dependencies, public entry points, menu-facing operations, trigger-facing operations, and ownership.
- Data sources, data lifecycle, ownership, movement, transformation, integrity rules, and synchronization model.
- Sheet architecture for every implemented operational, template, dashboard, report, archive, and system sheet.
- Column architecture, required/optional/generated/calculated/synchronization/validation/protected columns, and header normalization rules.
- Mapping architecture, including source-to-destination mapping, lookup rules, merge rules, primary-key rules, and synchronization behavior.
- Template architecture, including template lifecycle, dashboard-controlled templates, formatting strategy, smart refresh behavior, staged build flags, resizing, visibility, and protection behavior.
- Dashboard architecture, including configuration dashboard, timing dashboard, dashboard quality report, diagnostics, signoff, validation, and governance areas.
- Major processing modules, including purpose, inputs, outputs, dependencies, business rules, and subsystem relationships.
- Reporting architecture, including generation, dependencies, timing, validation, output standards, and quality signals.
- Validation framework, including preflight validation, template validation, configuration validation, workflow validation, data-integrity validation, and failure behavior.
- Error-handling framework, including recovery, logging, notification, fault isolation, validation failure behavior, and workflow busy flag protection.
- Performance framework, including batch operations, caching, in-memory transforms, Maps/Sets, minimized flushes, scalable sheet operations, and known high-complexity areas.
- Governance, including naming standards, protected standards, architecture decisions, versioning, approved patterns, public-interface stability, and safe-change requirements.
- Function organization by logical groups and ownership, not every individual function.
- Maintenance guidance for future development, dependency review, specification synchronization, validation, and release preparation.

