## 6. Required Sections

Generate the specification with the following top-level structure. Add appropriate lower-level subsections as needed while preserving hierarchy.

## Framework Overview

Include purpose, scope, objectives, framework philosophy, design principles, major components, and the current implementation baseline.

## Framework Architecture

Include overall architecture, processing architecture, module organization, subsystem relationships, execution model, framework layers, and dependency boundaries.

## Configuration Framework

Include configuration objects, runtime configuration, global constants, dashboard configuration, feature flags, version management, document properties, cache behavior, and configuration ownership.

## Workflow Architecture

Include overall workflow, process sequence, execution order, dependencies, entry points, public interfaces, menu operations, trigger operations, workflow ownership, and concurrency controls.

## Data Architecture

Include data sources, data lifecycle, data ownership, data movement, transformation rules, integrity rules, synchronization model, archive behavior, and retention behavior.

## Sheet Architecture

Document every implemented sheet category and notable sheet. For each sheet or sheet family, include purpose, lifecycle, creation, maintenance, processing, dependencies, relationships, visibility, protection, naming standards, and data ownership.

## Column Architecture

Include column definitions, required columns, optional columns, generated columns, calculated columns, synchronization columns, validation columns, protected columns, header normalization, and dashboard-defined column behavior.

## Mapping Architecture

Include source mapping, destination mapping, transformation rules, lookup rules, synchronization rules, merge rules, primary-key rules, and conflict-handling behavior.

## Template Architecture

Include template philosophy, lifecycle, formatting strategy, template synchronization, dashboard-controlled templates, smart refresh, staged build controls, template validation, and template standards.

## Dashboard Architecture

Include dashboard components, dashboard configuration, dashboard quality, dashboard validation, dashboard reporting, dashboard governance, dashboard sections, signoff behavior, timing integration, and diagnostic ownership.

## Processing Modules

Describe every major processing module at a subsystem level. Include purpose, inputs, outputs, dependencies, business rules, relationships, and ownership. Do not document every function individually.

## Reporting Architecture

Include reports, generation processes, dependencies, validation, timing, output standards, dashboards, summaries, diagnostics, and accepted quality signals.

## Validation Framework

Include validation strategy, framework validation, template validation, configuration validation, workflow validation, integrity validation, error detection, preflight gates, and fail-fast rules.

## Quality Assurance Framework

Include QA architecture, verification approach, audit strategy, framework health checks, diagnostic reports, dashboard quality checks, timing review, and acceptance criteria.

## Error Handling Framework

Include error management, recovery, logging, notification, fault isolation, validation failures, workflow busy flag handling, and safe termination behavior.

## Performance Framework

Include performance design, optimization strategy, runtime cache, memory usage, batch operations, scalable sheet manipulation, destructive-operation batching, dashboard timing, and high-complexity function notes.

## Framework Governance

Include engineering standards, naming standards, framework rules, protected standards, architecture decisions, approved patterns, versioning, public-interface stability, and safe-change controls.

## Function Organization

Document logical function groups, responsibilities, ownership, interactions, public entry points, workflow functions, validators, formatters, dashboard functions, utilities, and internal/private helpers. Use the function inventory for summary counts and group coverage.

## Framework Maintenance

Explain how future development should occur, how architecture should evolve, how governance is maintained, how specifications remain synchronized, how dependency review must precede removal or renaming, and how production changes should be validated.

## Appendices

Include at minimum:

- Framework terminology.
- Sheet inventory.
- Module inventory.
- Public entry point inventory.
- Workflow diagrams expressed as text or Mermaid-compatible fenced diagrams if appropriate.
- Configuration reference.
- Dashboard reference.
